docs.snippet: Bond prices sagged again on the Stock Exchange yesterday in the slowest trading for a full five-hour day since Nov. 11. Yesterday's turnover amounted to only $8,010,800, compared with $8,002,000 on Nov. 11. The only group to run counter to the...
docs.lead_paragraph: Bond prices sagged again on the Stock Exchange yesterday in the slowest trading for a full five-hour day since Nov. 11. Yesterday's turnover amounted to only $8,010,800, compared with $8,002,000 on Nov. 11. The only group to run counter to the general market was United States Government bonds which were bid up 2-32 to 14-32 points with the exception of one issue, the Treasury 4 1/4s.

docs.lead_paragraph: To Wall Street the violent advance on the Stock Exchange yesterday, following that of Thursday, indicated that speculative interests had not altered their original judgment of the proposed amendment to the Federal Reserve act. A badly frightened bear party continued to cover its commitments at swiftly rising prices, while other speculators proceeded to buy stock for long account.
